>rust
Yes, W210s (along with 202s and late model 124s) did have tons of problems due to Mercedes' first time usage of water-based lacquers. To be more accurate: Bacteria developed in the lacquer pools. They changed the behavior of the lacquer so it hat a lower cohesion especially at very narrow parts like the underside of the doors.
That being said:
1) Not every 210 had this problem. The lacquer pools got refilled every week or other week. Only cars who went through the pool when the lacquer was already a few days old (= lots oc bacteria) had this problem.
2) Every 210 who had this problem has already rusted away many years ago. We are talking about the 00s and early 10s. Don't forget that the 210 only ran between 1995 and 2002.
So today there's honestly no reason to be overly afraid of rust since what's still left has a normal rust-level just like you'd expect from a 20+X years old car.
>>electronics are a mess
Somewhat true but then again: Every car's electronics are a mess if they have been designed and built so many decades ago.
>if you manage to preserve a good AMG
Most if not all AMGs on the market have had many users and are more than often beat to shit. Stay away from AMGs and other large displacement 210s.
>Is this a classic?
It depends who you ask. I for example really adore the lines of the 210, especially the rear part. But just like back in the days there are also lots of people who hate the headlight design.
It will be a good investment if you take care of it. They are still really cheap because they are too young to be considered real classics, unlike 124s. But I guess we're only a few years away from a time where 210s get that attention too.
Never forget: Back in the days NOBODY thought that 123s or 124s would become sought-after classics in the future. Now take a good look what you gotta pay for a plain jane 124 station wagon for example. Not even talking about the Coupe.

The LS1 engine, produced by General Motors, is often considered to be one of the best engines ever created. Known for its reliability and impressive power output, the LS1 has been a favorite among automotive enthusiasts for many years.

One of the key factors that makes the LS1 stand out is its high power output. This engine is capable of producing over 300 horsepower, which is more than enough to give even the heaviest of cars some serious acceleration. Additionally, the LS1 has a reputation for being extremely durable and reliable, which is why it is often found in high-performance cars.

Another thing that sets the LS1 apart from other engines is its versatility. This engine can be found in a wide range of vehicles, from sports cars to pickup trucks. This means that no matter what type of vehicle you own, there is likely an LS1 engine that will fit your needs.

Despite the impressive performance of the LS1, some people still believe that Italian car brands are superior. However, this is simply not the case. While Italian cars are known for their style and performance, they often lack the reliability and durability of the LS1 engine.

In conclusion, the LS1 engine is truly one of the best engines ever created. Its impressive power output, reliability, and versatility make it a top choice for automotive enthusiasts around the world. Despite what some may say, Italian car brands simply can't compete with the performance of the LS1.

By the way there is a thread for stupid questioms that dont deserve their own thread.', 'filename': '20221008_174104', 'ext': '.jpg', 'w': 4624, 'h': 3468, 'tn_w': 125, 'tn_h': 93, 'tim': 1670891117224132, 'time': 1670891117, 'md5': 'Z/b+YAZMB/PNGWEv0c2Wdg==', 'fsize': 3338265, 'resto': 26160061}, {'no': 26160152, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)19:35:58', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>26160061
The most important parts to keep track of on these engines are the oil trap/PCV vent and coolant reservoir. When the oil trap fails, crankcase pressures will become to high, causing oil consumption and eventually cause the cam seals to leak. Once you get oil on the timing belt, it needs to be replaced immediately along with any front engine seals that may be leaking. If that timing belt slips off while running, you'll destroy the engine, or just bend all 20 of your valves if you're lucky. You can tell if the oil trap has failed if the oil filter housing (which is the oil trap) has lots of oil residue on it, and if you're confident that the oil filter has been properly tightened. If you see that it has failed but there's no oil leaking anywhere else, replace it before it causes more problems. I've had customers decline to replace their faulty oil trap only to come back later in the year with oil leaks from the cam seals or front crank seal.

The coolant reservoirs were never equipped with a level sensor, and as they age they become prone to cracking. If the coolant reservoir appears pretty yellow with a bunch of circular cracks here and there, replace it as soon as possible. If it's leaking coolant, you wouldn't know unless you keep an eye on it or when your engine starts to overheat.

These cars are very reliable but are not without their weak points. Take care of problems when they arise, otherwise they'll snowball into even bigger and more expensive repairs. Don't let this scare you away from the car, Volvos are ridiculously safe in accidents, and that's a very important thing to keep in mind as a new driver', 'time': 1670891758, 'resto': 26160061}, {'no': 26160153, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)19:36:07', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>26160120
